Chief Culprit Putin
Moscow—German, French and Swedish medical experts have unanimously stated that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, since Navalny survived, the relations between Russia and Germany have not deteriorated.
In order to demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel declared that Navalny is "a victim of persecution for freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond to it.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is responsible for the incident, the European Commission will impose another round of sanctions.
Nevertheless, according to the regulations of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time that the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political enemies.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergey Naryshkin, the head of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed that this was the act of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to tarnish the credibility of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly an overreach, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny incident has been more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a well-known political opponent just before the upcoming elections, and using a toxin developed by the former Soviet Union, is simply indefensible.
Especially considering that the people of neighboring Belarus are currently protesting against the August elections, this timing is particularly intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny incident was particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that did it, then this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics (the main antagonist in the movie Star Wars), interfering in the US election, inciting protests in France, luring Britain out of the EU, and supporting Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB officer, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why can Navalny flee to Germany? And why was he soon diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline to Germany is at risk of cancellation.
This assassination clearly was not worth it.
In fact, it has further fueled public opposition against the Russian authorities' misconduct.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies is even more excessive.
If such accusations are true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have revealed the fact that Novichok is a nerve agent.
More possibilities come from a conspiracy plotted by Putin's political inner circle.
It might be that Putin needs Navalny to shut up before the elections, or it might be because of his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, although loyal, are very stupid; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few involved know the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts have similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Public Inquiry Commission.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on abuses of power within the Russian judicial system.
Going further back, there is the poisoning of former KGB officer Alexander Litvinenko in 2006. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Just like the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was shot dead in an elevator in her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused enormous damage to the image of the Russian government.
This does not exonerate the Kremlin in any way.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the result the Kremlin wants, and pleasing their master Putin is the ultimate goal of the lackeys.
Loyalty is the only goal in Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning failed, they would not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find evidence of poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless of that, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly state their position, imposing sanctions on Russia even if their own economies are affected.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that have occurred in Russia are attributed to himself.
